    content: `
<h2>Lexical Change - New Words, Borrowed Words, Lost Words</h2>

<p>The vocabulary of English has never stopped growing. From its Germanic roots through centuries of borrowing, coinage, and adaptation, the English lexicon has expanded from perhaps 50,000 words in Old English to an estimated one million or more in Present Day English. <strong>Lexical change</strong> - the addition, loss, and transformation of words - is arguably the most visible and dynamic dimension of language change. It is also the dimension most closely tied to social, cultural, and technological change: new things need new names, contact with other cultures brings new words, and changing attitudes render old words obsolete or offensive. For IAL Unit 2, you must be able to identify, classify, and explain the processes of lexical change, using accurate terminology and historical examples.</p>

<div class="key-term"><strong>Key Term: Lexical Change</strong> - Changes in the vocabulary of a language over time, including the creation of new words (neologisms), the borrowing of words from other languages, the loss of words that fall out of use (archaisms), and changes in the meaning of existing words (semantic change).</div>

<h3>Word Formation Processes</h3>

<p>English creates new words through a range of productive processes. Understanding these processes is essential for analysing how the lexicon has changed historically and how it continues to change today.</p>

<p><strong>Affixation</strong> (also called derivation) involves adding prefixes or suffixes to existing words to create new ones. English has a rich inventory of affixes: prefixes like <em>un-, re-, pre-, mis-, dis-, over-</em> and suffixes like <em>-ness, -ment, -tion, -able, -ful, -less, -ise, -ly</em>. Many of these affixes were borrowed from Latin and French. Affixation is one of the most productive word-formation processes in English and has been throughout its history. Recent examples include <em>unfriend</em> (un- + friend, used as a verb), <em>clickbait</em> (click + bait, with the suffix-like element), and <em>mansplain</em> (man + explain, a blend that also involves affixation patterns).</p>

<p><strong>Compounding</strong> involves combining two or more existing words to create a new word with a distinct meaning. Old English was rich in compounds (kennings like "whale-road"), and compounding remains highly productive today: <em>smartphone, laptop, download, livestream, cryptocurrency, cyberbullying</em>. Compounds can be written as one word, two words, or hyphenated, and the convention often changes over time (e-mail became email, web site became website).</p>

<p><strong>Conversion</strong> (also called zero derivation or functional shift) involves using an existing word in a new grammatical class without changing its form. Shakespeare was a master of this process. In modern English, conversion remains highly productive: we <em>text</em> people (noun to verb), <em>google</em> things (proper noun to verb), take a <em>big ask</em> (verb to noun), and go for a <em>run</em> (verb to noun). Conversion demonstrates the flexibility of English morphology.</p>

<p><strong>Blending</strong> involves merging parts of two words to create a new one: <em>brunch</em> (breakfast + lunch), <em>smog</em> (smoke + fog), <em>blog</em> (web + log), <em>podcast</em> (iPod + broadcast), <em>staycation</em> (stay + vacation). Blending has become increasingly productive in modern English, particularly in marketing, technology, and informal language.</p>

<p><strong>Clipping</strong> involves shortening an existing word: <em>phone</em> (from telephone), <em>bus</em> (from omnibus), <em>exam</em> (from examination), <em>flu</em> (from influenza), <em>app</em> (from application). Many clipped forms eventually replace the original in everyday use.</p>

<p><strong>Acronymy</strong> involves forming words from the initial letters of a phrase: <em>NATO</em> (North Atlantic Treaty Organization), <em>scuba</em> (self-contained underwater breathing apparatus), <em>laser</em> (light amplification by stimulated emission of radiation). Some acronyms become so embedded in the language that speakers forget their origins.</p>

<p><strong>Back-formation</strong> involves creating a new word by removing what appears to be an affix from an existing word: <em>edit</em> (from editor), <em>televise</em> (from television), <em>babysit</em> (from babysitter), <em>enthuse</em> (from enthusiasm). The "derived" word actually came first, and the "root" was created afterwards by analogy.</p>

<div class="key-term"><strong>Key Term: Neologism</strong> - A newly coined word or expression, or a new meaning for an existing word. Neologisms may enter the language through any word-formation process including borrowing, coinage, blending, clipping, or conversion. Some neologisms become established; many disappear after brief use.</div>

<h3>Borrowing</h3>

<p>English has borrowed more freely and extensively from other languages than almost any other language in the world. This openness to borrowing reflects England's (and later Britain's and America's) history of invasion, colonisation, trade, and cultural exchange. The major waves of borrowing include: Old Norse (Viking period: <em>sky, egg, they, window, skill</em>), Norman French (post-1066: <em>government, justice, beauty, fashion</em>), Latin (Renaissance: <em>education, explain, democracy</em>), and words from languages encountered through global exploration and colonialism - Hindi (<em>jungle, bungalow, shampoo</em>), Arabic (<em>algebra, algorithm, zero</em>), Indigenous Australian languages (<em>kangaroo, boomerang</em>), Japanese (<em>tsunami, karate, emoji</em>), and many others. In the modern era, English continues to borrow from other languages while simultaneously being a major source of borrowings for other languages worldwide.</p>

<h3>Archaisms and Obsolescence</h3>

<p>Just as new words are constantly being created, old words are constantly falling out of use. Words that survive in the language but sound old-fashioned are called <strong>archaisms</strong> - words like <em>thou, hither, forsooth, whence, perchance</em>. Words that have disappeared entirely from the language are described as <strong>obsolete</strong> - Old English words like <em>dryhten</em> (lord) or <em>beorscealc</em> (drinking companion) have no modern equivalent or continuation. Words become obsolete for various reasons: the thing they refer to disappears (many words for types of medieval armour), they are replaced by borrowed alternatives (Old English <em>here</em> was replaced by the French borrowing <em>army</em>), or social change makes them taboo or irrelevant.</p>

<div class="examiner-tip"><strong>Examiner Tip:</strong> When discussing lexical change in exam responses, always use the correct technical terminology for word-formation processes. Rather than saying a word was "made up," specify whether it was formed through affixation, compounding, conversion, blending, clipping, back-formation, or borrowing. This demonstrates precise linguistic knowledge.</div>

<h3>Lexical Change as a Mirror of Social Change</h3>

<p>The vocabulary of a language reflects the culture and preoccupations of its speakers. When new technologies emerge, new words follow: the twentieth and twenty-first centuries have produced <em>television, computer, internet, email, hashtag, selfie, cryptocurrency, and algorithm</em> (repurposed from its original mathematical meaning). When social attitudes change, vocabulary changes too: terms once considered neutral may become offensive, and new terms are created to replace them. The study of lexical change is therefore never purely linguistic - it is always also social, cultural, and political.</p>
`,
