    duration: '60 min',
    content: `
<h2>Analysing Historical Texts - Systematic Comparison</h2>

<p>The ability to analyse historical texts systematically is the core practical skill of IAL Unit 2. In the exam, you will be presented with texts from different periods and asked to compare them, identifying and explaining the linguistic differences. This is not simply a matter of spotting "old-fashioned" words - it requires a methodical approach that examines every level of language: <strong>orthography</strong> (spelling), <strong>lexis</strong> (vocabulary), <strong>semantics</strong> (meaning), <strong>grammar</strong> (morphology and syntax), <strong>phonology</strong> (sound, where evidence is available), and <strong>pragmatics</strong> (how language functions in context). This module provides a framework for systematic analysis.</p>

<div class="key-term"><strong>Key Term: Diachronic Analysis</strong> - The study of language change over time, examining how linguistic features have evolved from one period to another. This contrasts with synchronic analysis, which examines language at a single point in time. IAL Unit 2 primarily requires diachronic analysis.</div>

<h3>A Framework for Historical Text Analysis</h3>

<p>When presented with a historical text, work through the following levels of analysis systematically. Not every text will show changes at every level, but checking each level ensures a thorough response.</p>

<h3>1. Orthography (Spelling)</h3>

<p>Spelling is often the most immediately noticeable difference between historical and modern texts. Look for: <strong>variable spellings</strong> (the same word spelled differently within the same text or differently from the modern standard); <strong>interchangeable letters</strong> (u/v, i/j, long s/round s in older texts); <strong>absence of apostrophes</strong> in possessives (pre-eighteenth-century texts rarely use apostrophes consistently); <strong>different conventions</strong> for consonant doubling, silent letters, and word boundaries; and <strong>capitalisation patterns</strong> (Early Modern texts often capitalise nouns in the German fashion). When discussing spelling differences, always distinguish between genuine changes in the writing system and mere variability that existed before standardisation imposed uniformity.</p>

<h3>2. Lexis (Vocabulary)</h3>

<p>Examine the vocabulary for: <strong>archaisms</strong> - words that are no longer in common use (<em>thee, thou, hath, doth, wherefore, hither</em>); <strong>false friends</strong> - words that look like modern words but had different meanings in the period (<em>nice</em> meaning "foolish," <em>meat</em> meaning "food," <em>prevent</em> meaning "come before"); <strong>borrowings</strong> that reveal the period of the text (heavy Latinate vocabulary suggests the Renaissance period or later); <strong>word-formation patterns</strong> that differ from modern conventions; and <strong>functional vocabulary</strong> - the use of pronouns, conjunctions, and prepositions that differ from modern usage.</p>

<h3>3. Semantics (Meaning)</h3>

<p>Closely related to lexis, semantic analysis examines whether words carry different meanings in the historical text compared to their modern usage. This requires careful contextual reading - a word's meaning must be deduced from its context in the text, not assumed to be the same as its modern meaning. False friends are the most obvious semantic challenge, but subtler shifts in connotation, register, and implication are also important.</p>

<h3>4. Grammar (Morphology and Syntax)</h3>

<p>Grammatical analysis is often the richest area for historical comparison. Look for: <strong>inflectional differences</strong> - verb endings like <em>-eth</em> (third person singular, as in "he giveth") and <em>-est</em> (second person singular, as in "thou givest"); <strong>pronoun differences</strong> - the use of "thou/thee/thy/thine" and "ye" alongside "you"; <strong>word order differences</strong> - object-verb order, verb-second constructions, or other non-SVO patterns; <strong>negation patterns</strong> - multiple negation or negation without "do" ("I know not" rather than "I do not know"); <strong>absence of do-periphrasis</strong> - questions formed without "do" ("Know you this man?" rather than "Do you know this man?"); <strong>different auxiliary constructions</strong>; and <strong>agreement patterns</strong> that differ from modern usage.</p>

<div class="examiner-tip"><strong>Examiner Tip:</strong> The best analytical responses do not simply list differences - they explain them. For every feature you identify, state what it is (using correct terminology), give a specific example from the text, explain what the modern equivalent would be, and where possible place the change in its historical context. The formula is: identify, exemplify, compare, contextualise.</div>

<h3>5. Discourse and Pragmatics</h3>

<p>Examine how the text functions as a communicative act. Consider: <strong>register</strong> - is the text formal or informal, and how does its level of formality compare with modern conventions for the same genre? <strong>Politeness strategies</strong> - does the text use forms of address, hedging, or indirectness that differ from modern norms? <strong>Genre conventions</strong> - does the text follow conventions that are different from those of the equivalent modern genre (for example, early letters often used much more elaborate openings and closings than modern letters)? <strong>Audience assumptions</strong> - what does the text assume about its audience's knowledge, social position, and expectations?</p>

<h3>6. Contextualising Your Analysis</h3>

<p>The strongest responses place linguistic features in their historical context. If a text uses heavy Latinate vocabulary, this may indicate that it was written during or after the Renaissance, when learned borrowing from Latin was at its height. If it uses "thou" and "you" interchangeably, this may indicate Early Modern usage before "thou" was fully lost. If it uses multiple negation, this is standard usage for texts before the prescriptive prohibition in the eighteenth century. Contextualising linguistic features demonstrates deep understanding and moves your analysis beyond mere description to genuine explanation.</p>

<h3>Structuring Your Response</h3>

<p>When writing a comparative analysis of historical texts, there are two main structural approaches. The <strong>text-by-text</strong> approach analyses one text fully before moving to the other, then draws comparisons. The <strong>feature-by-feature</strong> approach organises the response around linguistic features (spelling, lexis, grammar, etc.), comparing both texts under each heading. The feature-by-feature approach generally produces more effective comparisons because it keeps the two texts in constant dialogue, making similarities and differences explicit. Whichever approach you choose, ensure that your response is organised clearly, uses accurate terminology consistently, and provides specific textual evidence for every claim.</p>

<div class="common-mistake"><strong>Common Mistake:</strong> Students sometimes describe features of historical texts as "wrong" or "incorrect." This is anachronistic. Before standardisation, there was no single "correct" form of English, and features like variable spelling, multiple negation, and -eth verb endings were standard usage in their periods. Always describe them as features of the period, not as mistakes.</div>

<h3>Using the Language Levels as a Checklist</h3>

<p>Think of the language levels - orthography, lexis, semantics, grammar, phonology, pragmatics - as a checklist. For each text, work through each level and note any features that differ from Present Day English. Then compare your notes across the two texts to identify both shared features (which might indicate a similar date or genre) and differences (which might indicate different periods, regions, or registers). This systematic approach ensures that you do not miss important features and that your analysis is comprehensive rather than piecemeal.</p>
`,
